<br>
To everyone who feels the need to debate the literal definitions of &quot;human&quot; and &quot;coward&quot;, maybe you should cut some people some slack, eh?<br>
<br>
Dear God, if an event like what happened Tuesday isn't enough incentive to put the &quot;devil's advocate&quot; crap on hold for issues that really don't matter, than what is?<br>
<br>
I'm sure that whether the terrorists were literally &quot;inhuman&quot;, &quot;non-human&quot;, &quot;human monsters&quot; or &quot;terrible people&quot; really makes a big difference to the 1000's who were killed.<br>
<br>
This kind of BS debate feels like an insult to their memory to me... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/uealan01.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ealan01</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 182<br> <font color=#E9D756>(9/13/01 4:32 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrfrm18.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=41.topic&index=22>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Our Freedom Has almost been taken away BITCH !</span><hr size=1> I'll speak to the WWII points and the Native American points now, in this seperate post.<br>
<br>
Cerulean summed it up quite nicely, but I'll just add that at different points in history, all nations have engaged in monstrous behavior.<br>
<br>
During times of war, many people are forced to become, or become, monsters.  I wonder, though, who stands more guilty in WWII?  The Japanese, who murdered MILLIONS of innocent Chinese through torture and dismemberment in concentration camps; ever see &quot;the Rape of Nanking&quot;?  The Germans, who attempted the systematic genocide of a segment of the human race?  Or the Americans, who were, horribly, the first and only nation in history to use nuclear weapons in an attempt to stop the mounting casualties in an unrelenting Japan?  Japan has said that they would have fought any invasion until their last citizen was dead, by the way.<br>
<br>
Why does ANY of this have ANYTHING to do with the actions of terrorists?  I simply don't understand the logic whereby you must use restraint in judging outrageous actions *today* because of &quot;sins of the past&quot;.<br>
<br>
Funny that people can sympathize with Japan over Hiroshima, but can't seem to extend the same line of reasoning to feel bad for the US today.  Japan, at the time, was a far greater force of evil than modern America.<br>
<br>
I wonder, also, if this had happened in Germany, would people be arguing &quot;well, Germany was pretty damn bad in WWII, so they can't complain&quot;.  Why is this kind of BS reasoning reserved for the US?<br>
<br>
